\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.1}{\ignorespaces High-level system architecture showing the end-to-end pipeline from schema ingestion through query generation, validation, labeling, and active learning to final model evaluation. The dashed feedback loop indicates iterative refinement through multiple active learning rounds.}}{14}{figure.caption.5}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4.2}{\ignorespaces Entity-relationship diagram of the IMDB database schema used in experiments. Primary keys (PK) and foreign keys (FK) are annotated. The \texttt {title\_principals} table serves as a junction table connecting titles to people.}}{18}{figure.caption.6}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.1}{\ignorespaces Structure of the LLM prompt template, consisting of five hierarchically organized components that guide the model from context understanding to constrained output generation.}}{23}{figure.caption.8}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5.2}{\ignorespaces Multi-layer validation pipeline for LLM-generated queries. Each layer progressively filters invalid queries, with rejected queries logged for analysis. Valid queries proceed to the MSCN format conversion stage.}}{29}{figure.caption.9}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6.1}{\ignorespaces Complete MSCN architecture. Each query component (samples, predicates, joins) passes through a dedicated two-layer MLP with dropout, followed by masked mean pooling. The pooled representations are concatenated and processed through an output MLP with sigmoid activation to produce a normalized cardinality estimate $\hat {y} \in [0, 1]$.}}{39}{figure.caption.15}%
\addvspace {10\p@ }
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.1}{\ignorespaces Combined structural feature distributions of the generated query workload. Left: number of tables per query. Center: number of join conditions per query. Right: number of filter predicates per query.}}{47}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.2}{\ignorespaces Distribution of the number of tables per generated query.}}{47}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.3}{\ignorespaces Distribution of the number of filter predicates per query.}}{47}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.4}{\ignorespaces Distribution of true cardinalities for labeled queries ($\log _{10}$ scale). The distribution spans from single-digit cardinalities to tens of millions of rows, ensuring comprehensive coverage of the selectivity spectrum.}}{48}{figure.caption.23}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.5}{\ignorespaces Active learning curve showing validation median Q-error versus number of labeled queries. The decreasing trend demonstrates that the model's estimation accuracy improves as more informative queries are labeled and added to the training set in each active learning round.}}{49}{figure.caption.24}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.6}{\ignorespaces Training loss curves across active learning rounds. The decreasing loss trajectory across rounds indicates that the model benefits from the progressively expanding and more informative training set.}}{49}{figure.caption.25}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.7}{\ignorespaces Predicted vs.\ actual cardinality for the final trained model (log-log scale). Points clustering around the diagonal indicate accurate predictions across the full cardinality range.}}{50}{figure.caption.26}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.8}{\ignorespaces Cumulative distribution function (CDF) of Q-errors for the final model.}}{50}{figure.caption.27}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.9}{\ignorespaces Q-error box plots per active learning round showing improving accuracy.}}{50}{figure.caption.27}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7.10}{\ignorespaces Pipeline summary dashboard showing key metrics from query generation, labeling, training, and evaluation across all active learning rounds.}}{51}{figure.caption.28}%
